{"Body": "<!-- p.p1 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; text-align: right; font: 13.0px 'Helvetica Neue'} p.p2 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; text-align: justify; text-indent: 10.0px; font: 9.0px 'Whitney HTF'} span.s1 {letter-spacing: -0.1px} -->Darren O&rsquo;Gorman\n\nSF Natural Science\n\n<strong>Welfare Officer</strong>\n\nContinuing the recent trend of having the LGBT Auditor as a candidate for the Welfare Office, Darren O&rsquo;Gorman has thrown his hat into the ring as the only male in the race.\n\nThe second year Natural Sciences student has shown considerable commitment to the LGBT cause, as evidenced by his swift rise to the position of Auditor.\n\nIn his first year, O&rsquo;Gorman was Publicity Officer of the LGBT and worked hard to bring the LGBT to a wider audience. O&rsquo;Gorman also claims that he has been &ldquo;involved with every Welfare campaign since I&rsquo;ve come to college.&rdquo; Added to this, O&rsquo;Gorman was a tutor for Voluntary Tuition Program.\n\nAs regards improvements that could be made to the way the SU operates, O&rsquo;Gorman says that &ldquo;the structures of the Student&rsquo;s Union should be more transparent. I want every student to be aware of and comfortable with the services of the SU being their first point of call if they ever want help or advice.&rdquo;\n\nOne area where O&rsquo;Gorman sees potential for improvement is the general availability of the SU&rsquo;s welfare service. &ldquo;I would aim to make the service that the Welfare Officer provides a more integrated service,&rdquo; says O&rsquo;Gorman. &ldquo;I would like to extend welfare services into off campus clinics&rdquo;\n\nO&rsquo;Gorman also sees problems with how College deals with students in need of welfare services.\n\n&ldquo;Welfare services aren&rsquo;t always easily accessible,&rdquo; said the Clare man. &ldquo;I want college services to understand how they can best serve the needs of the student body and help students access the support that they are entitled to. A strong Student&rsquo;s Union is the best mechanism to do this.&rdquo;\n\nO&rsquo;Gorman is of the opinion that dialogue between college services and the Welfare office is the most important way to ensure the best quality service for all students.\n\nO&rsquo;Gorman is also keenly aware of the importance of the welfare office in this challenging economic times. &ldquo;In times of difficult financial circumstances for the country as a whole,&rdquo; O&rsquo;Gorman said to The University Times. &ldquo;The Welfare office has the potential to be the most important point of contact with the Student&rsquo;s Union for the student body. I would make sure that lobbying on the implementation of the Students Support Bill would continue to ensure an efficient grant system came to fruition.I would make sure to defend Welfare and SU budgets in an effort to protect the most vulnerable in college.&rdquo;", "Imageurl": "<!-- p.p1 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; text-align: right; font: 13.0px 'Helvetica Neue'} p.p2 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; text-align: justify; text-indent: 10.0px; font: 9.0px 'Whitney HTF'} span.s1 {letter-spacing: -0.1px} -->Darren O&rsquo;Gorman\n\nSF Natural Science\n\n<strong>Welfare Officer</strong>\n\nContinuing the recent trend of having the LGBT Auditor as a candidate for the Welfare Office, Darren O&rsquo;Gorman has thrown his hat into the ring as the only male in the race.\n\nThe second year Natural Sciences student has shown considerable commitment to the LGBT cause, as evidenced by his swift rise to the position of Auditor.\n\nIn his first year, O&rsquo;Gorman was Publicity Officer of the LGBT and worked hard to bring the LGBT to a wider audience. O&rsquo;Gorman also claims that he has been &ldquo;involved with every Welfare campaign since I&rsquo;ve come to college.&rdquo; Added to this, O&rsquo;Gorman was a tutor for Voluntary Tuition Program.\n\nAs regards improvements that could be made to the way the SU operates, O&rsquo;Gorman says that &ldquo;the structures of the Student&rsquo;s Union should be more transparent. I want every student to be aware of and comfortable with the services of the SU being their first point of call if they ever want help or advice.&rdquo;\n\nOne area where O&rsquo;Gorman sees potential for improvement is the general availability of the SU&rsquo;s welfare service. &ldquo;I would aim to make the service that the Welfare Officer provides a more integrated service,&rdquo; says O&rsquo;Gorman. &ldquo;I would like to extend welfare services into off campus clinics&rdquo;\n\nO&rsquo;Gorman also sees problems with how College deals with students in need of welfare services.\n\n&ldquo;Welfare services aren&rsquo;t always easily accessible,&rdquo; said the Clare man. &ldquo;I want college services to understand how they can best serve the needs of the student body and help students access the support that they are entitled to. A strong Student&rsquo;s Union is the best mechanism to do this.&rdquo;\n\nO&rsquo;Gorman is of the opinion that dialogue between college services and the Welfare office is the most important way to ensure the best quality service for all students.\n\nO&rsquo;Gorman is also keenly aware of the importance of the welfare office in this challenging economic times. &ldquo;In times of difficult financial circumstances for the country as a whole,&rdquo; O&rsquo;Gorman said to The University Times. &ldquo;The Welfare office has the potential to be the most important point of contact with the Student&rsquo;s Union for the student body. I would make sure that lobbying on the implementation of the Students Support Bill would continue to ensure an efficient grant system came to fruition.I would make sure to defend Welfare and SU budgets in an effort to protect the most vulnerable in college.&rdquo;", "Thumb_nail": "http://universitytimes.ie/wp-content/uploads/2013/utlogo.jpg", "ID": "235", "Heading": "SU ELECTION CANDIDATE: Darren O&rsquo;Gorman"}